Ihave controverted Mn. Gladstone’s view oi the relation of the Aeneid to the Homeric poems, as expressed in the third volume of his ‘ Stadios? In my former volume I vas thought,I believe, to have disparaged unduly Virgil's claim to originality: I may now be considered to be taking the opposite side, in vindicating his right to be criticized independently of Homer. Both views ere,I believe, true, and therefore consistent: hut it is possible of course so to maintain either as to appear unmindful of the other.

My obligations to my former colleague, Mr. Goldwin Smith, are unfortunately confined in the present volume almost wholly to the notes on the First Book, which we originally composed together in 1853: and even they have since been so completely recast that it would be difficult now to point to any part of them

as specially due to him. I need not say that Ι have still had the benefit of Mr. Long's assistance.

JOHN OONINGTON.
